{"title_page": "Ruy Guerra", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian-Mozambican film director and actor}}\n{{Portuguese name|Guerra|Coelho Pereira}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ruy Guerra\n| image       = Presen\u00e7a do 5x Favela no Back2Black Festival!2.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| birth_name  = Ruy Alexandre Guerra Coelho Pereira\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1931|8|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Maputo]], [[Portuguese Mozambique]]\n| citizenship = {{hlist|Portugal|Brazil}}\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| othername   = \n| occupation  = {{hlist|Film director|screenwriter}}\n| yearsactive = 1954\u2013present\n| spouse      = [[Leila Diniz]] (1971\u20131972)<br />[[Cl\u00e1udia Ohana]] (1981\u20131984)\n}}\n'''Ruy Alexandre Guerra Coelho Pereira''' (born August 22, 1931) is a Portuguese-Brazilian [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]]. Guerra was born a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] citizen in Louren\u00e7o Marques (today [[Maputo]]) in [[Mozambique]], when it was still a Portuguese colony.\n\n== Biography ==\n[[File:Ruy Guerra (1972).tif|thumb|Ruy Guerra, 1972.]]\nGuerra studied at [[IDHEC]] film school in [[Paris]] from 1952. In 1958 he started his career as an assistant director in several French films. He subsequntly immigrated to [[Brazil]], where he directed his first feature film, ''[[Os Cafajestes]]'' (1962). It was entered into the [[12th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0055821/awards |title=IMDB.com: Awards for Os Cafajestes |accessdate=2010-02-07 |work=imdb.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Guerra directed ''[[Os Fuzis]]'', which placed him in the forefront of the emerging [[Cinema Novo]] movement. The film was entered into the [[14th Berlin International Film Festival]] where it won the [[Silver Bear|Silver Bear Extraordinary Jury Prize]].<ref name=\"berlinale 1964\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1964/03_preistr_ger_1964/03_Preistraeger_1964.html |title=Berlinale 1964: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-02-19 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nAfter that he directed the international production ''[[Tendres Chasseurs]]'' (1969) starring [[Sterling Hayden]], and ''[[Of Gods and the Undead|Os Deuses e os Mortos]]'' (1970). The tumultuous political landscape in 1970's Brazil forced Guerra to stop filming until 1976, when he directed ''[[A Queda]]''. The film was entered into the [[28th Berlin International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Jury Grand Prix|Silver Bear - Special Jury Prize]].<ref name=\"berlinale 1978\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1978/03_preistr_ger_1978/03_Preistraeger_1978.html |title=Berlinale 1978: Prize Winners |accessdate=2010-08-04 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980 he returned to Mozambique where he shot ''[[Mueda, Mem\u00f3ria e Massacre]]'', that country's first feature film. While in Mozambique, Guerra shot many short films and helped the creation of the National Institute for Cinema.\n\nIn 1982 Guerra shot ''[[Er\u00e9ndira (film)|Er\u00e9ndira]]'' in [[Mexico]], based on the work by [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]. He also directed the musical comedy ''[[A \u00d3pera do Malandro]]'' (1985), based on [[Chico Buarque]]'s free theatrical adaptation of [[Bertold Brecht]]'s ''[[Threepenny Opera]]''; the TV film ''[[Os Amores Dif\u00edceis]]'', another adaptation of Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez; and ''[[Kuarup (film)|Kuarup]]'' (1989). In 2000 Guerra's ''[[Turbulence (2000 film)|Estorvo]]'' was nominated for the [[Golden Palm]] at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5142/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Turbulence |accessdate=2009-10-11|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> It was Guerra's third nomination in the festival, after ''Er\u00eandira'' and ''Kuarup''. His 2004 film ''[[Portugal S.A.]]'' was the only film he did in Portugal and entered into the [[26th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow2004\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2004 |title=26th Moscow International Film Festival (2004) |accessdate=2013-04-07 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403123603/http://moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2004 |archivedate=2013-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nGuerra has appeared in many films as an actor; he is perhaps best known to international audiences for his performance as the doomed [[Pedro de Urs\u00faa]] in [[Werner Herzog]]'s ''[[Aguirre, the Wrath of God]]'' (1972).\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1971, Guerra married Brazilian actress [[Leila Diniz]]. Diniz was killed the following year in the crash of [[Japan Airlines Flight 471]] in India.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|+ Key\n|-\n|align=center style=\"width:50px;background-color:#CEE8F0\"|{{dagger}}\n|Indicates a work made for TV\n|align=center style=\"width:50px;background-color:#FFECC8\"|{{double-dagger}}\n|Indicates a short film\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of films directed by Ruy Guerra\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Original title\n! scope=\"col\" | English release title\n! scope=\"col\" | Language(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1954\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color:#FFECC8;\" | ''Quand Le Soleil Dort'' {{sup|{{double-dagger}}}}\n|\n| French\n| French production.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1962\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Unscrupulous Ones|Os Cafajestes]]''\n| ''The Unscrupulous Ones'' / ''The Miscreants'' / ''The Hustlers''\n| Portuguese\n| Guerra's first Brazilian production.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1964\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Guns (film)|Os Fuzis]]''\n| ''The Guns''\n| Portuguese\n| Brazilian-argentinian co-production.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1969\n! scope=\"row\" 